<DOC><DOCNO> AP881004-0227 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 0019EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   10-04 0522</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0545</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Oil futures prices have tested lows not seen intwo years amid indications that Saudi Arabia might boost theiroutput to try to pressure other OPEC oil producers to restrictproduction.   The November contract of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmarkU.S. crude skidded 31 cents a barrel Monday to settle at $13.06 abarrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange. Crude prices had notclosed that low since August 1986.   The price of crude has skidded $2 a barrel over the past fiveweeks. But experts say consumers probably won't benefitsignificantly unless crude holds at these depressed levels for anextended period.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Orders to U.S. factories for manufacturedgoods surged 3.1 percent in August, the government says.   The Commerce Department said Monday that orders rose $6.8billion to a seasonally adjusted $226.6 billion, rebounding from a3.6 percent decline in July, the worst in 18 months.   The overall orders number has been influenced in recent monthsby wide swings in orders for transportation equipment, particularlyaircraft.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Economists blame rising interest rates andoverbuilding in some regions for a 0.6 percent decline inconstruction spending in August.   The Commerce Department said Monday that building activitydeclined to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $396.1 billion inAugust, following a revised 0.7 percent gain in July. The Julyfigure had been preliminarily reported as a strong 1.2 percent gain.   For the first eight months of the year, activity was up only 0.4percent over the same period in 1987, failing to keep pace with the1.4 percent increase in construction costs.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Transportation Department has setfuel-economy standards for 1989 passenger cars at 26.5 miles pergallon of gasoline, a level the nation's two largest automakers saythey could meet without layoffs and production cuts.   The department's decision disclosed Monday kept the fuel economyaverage required for each auto manufacturer from increasing to the27.5 mpg enacted by Congress in 1975. Since 1986, the automakershave been required to meet a 26 mpg standard.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Ninety percent of Americans believe thegovernment should require automakers to build cars with greaterfuel-efficiency, according to a poll commissioned byenvironmentalists.   Two-thirds of the respondents believe they will see anotherenergy crisis that could bring back gasoline lines, but nearlythree-quarters oppose a 30-cent increase in the gasoline tax aimedat discouraging consumption, according to the survey releasedMonday by the Analysis Group Inc., a New Haven, Conn.-based pollingfirm.   The poll was conducted for The Communications Consortium, apublic relations firm representing environmental groups.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Supreme Court has closed a chapter in thelargest municipal bond default in U.S. history, dismissing claimsby investors who lost money from the Washington Public Power SupplySystem's doomed nuclear power project.   The court let stand on Monday a ruling that dismissed some keyinvestor claims triggered by the $2.25 billion bond default. Italso rejected an appeal by the bond counsel in the case seekingadditional legal protection.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>